Confirmed. `coinbase::convert(pve_ct, blob.ct)` does NOT enforce strict trailing-byte checks. It just runs `pve_ct.convert(converter)` and returns rv_error. So a blob where Q has m < n entries but the rest is well-formed will deserialize successfully (no error), with trailing bytes ignored.

Now let me carefully re-verify the deserialization flow in `ec_pve_batch_t::convert`:

```cpp
void convert(coinbase::converter_t& converter) {
  if (int(Q.size()) != n) { converter.set_error(); return; }  // Q.size()==n here (constructor), passes
  converter.convert(Q, L, b);   // Q.clear(); reads count=m; Q.resize(m); reads m points; then L, b
  for (int i = 0; i < kappa; i++) {
    converter.convert(rows[i].x_bin);
    converter.convert(rows[i].r);
    converter.convert(rows[i].c);
  }
}
```

After this, `Q.size() == m` (attacker-controlled), but `n` field is still the constructor value. The rows are deserialized normally (kappa=SEC_P_COM rows).

This confirms the candidate's mechanical claim about the no-op pre-check.

Now let me verify there are no other length checks I'm missing. Let me check `SEC_P_COM` (kappa value), `genPVELabelWithPoint`, and confirm the curve check loop at line 165-167 doesn't reject m<n.

